Jonathan Fry wrote:
>
>Consider, first, what will happen if the Impeachments do not pass.  On
>the one hand, a Rebellion might occur,

The fault of that lies with the Rebels.  It is in their power
to stop it.  

>On the other hand, if
>the Rebellion does not occur, nearly all of the Offices will be held
>by the few members of the Threat, adding further imbalance to the VT
>distribution and such.

"Imbalance?"  If you measure VT imbalance as VTs held by Threat
vs. VTs held by non-Threat, I suppose it would.  The only
VT imbalance I care about, however, is VTs held by me vs
VTs held by everyone else.

Now, consider that I recently lost an Election for Notary
(no hard feelings, I hope, Murphy?  Certainly none on this
side), even with the backing of the Threat.  Thus, it seems
to me highly unlikely that in another Rebellion, I would
win any elections except that for Rulekeepor.  In other words:
No Rebellion: I am Rulekeepor, but hold no other offices.
Rebellion: I am Rulekeepor, but hold no other offices.
In either case, the VT imbalance--as I define it--is the same.

>If, however, you and a few others vote for the Impeachments, we will
>be able to avoid the complete deposition of all non-Threat Players in
>Office.  We will be able to hold less Elections and keep people like
>yourself and Kolja A. in office.

I consider it an honor to be named Rulekeepor in perpetuity, but
I do *not* take that to mean I can suddenly ignore the will of
Agorans.  There is no shame in my having to run for re-election,
at any time--if there comes a time when I cannot win an election
for Rulekeepor, then I do not deserve to be Rulekeepor.

In other words: First, I won't be blackmailed into voting
for impeachments on the grounds that no impeachments will lead
to Rebellion.  Second, if there is a Rebellion, either
a) I win my election as Rulekeepor, in which case no harm
is done, or b) I lose my election as Rulekeepor, in which
case I do not deserve to be Rulekeepor anyway.  I feel the
same holds true for Kolja and the Ambassadorship.

>It is thus in this spirit that I ask you to vote FOR all Impeachments,
>except in the unfortunate case of Michael.

What if I said I would Rebel if Michael were not impeached?  (I
ask merely hypothetically.)  Would you find that sufficient cause
to vote FOR the impeachment of Michael?

Chuck

