> 
> Dr. Jeffrey L. Caruso writes:
> > If the original revolt had been purely for the purposes of grabbing power,
> > I would not have supported it myself.  Likewise if your present Impeachment
> > is for such purposes, I don't expect people to support it.
> 
> Can I ask where you got the idea that I'm using the Impeachments to
> keep my "clique" in Office or "grab for power"?  First, I don't even
> have a "clique" (I'm too new for that); second, I wasn't planning to
> run in any of the upcoming Elections.

Isn't it clear that you are part of quite a strong clique which just
recently formed, ie the "get Threat out of power" clique? Who do you
intend will fill the Offices that you oust us from? Are they not members
of that clique? 

Not that I blame you for this, but your concern to keep power out of 
our hands is pretty much equivalent to our concern to hold on to it,
isn't it?

You may claim to be working to spread the Offices around a bit, to have
no strong concentration of power, but if that is the case, why are you
trying to Impeach us for all the Offices we hold? Why not just select
about half of them, and let us keep the rest? 

I don't accuse you of wrongdoing, you are just playing the game. And
part of that is playing to win. I am also playing to win, as recent
events have shown. I just don't buy your innocent arguments that you
are doing this for the good of the game.

Of course, by all means resist our hold on power. It wouldn't be 
much fun if you didn't. And, if it helps your cause, appeal to other
players for the good of the game in order to help you do so, but 
don't expect us to sit idly by and let you do so. Agora is a game of
propaganda as much as any other form of politics. It may not be the
Public Forum, but I strongly believe that this game is won or lost in
agora-discussion. 

